The Core AI Stack (clean mental model)

1. Perception Layer (Sensing the world)

This is where raw reality gets turned into data.

Key types:
	•	CV (Computer Vision) → images, video
	•	ASR (Automatic Speech Recognition) → speech → text
	•	Sensor fusion → LiDAR, radar, GPS, etc.

Function:

“What is out there?”

This is the eyes + ears.

⸻

2. Representation Layer (Structuring what was seen)

Turns raw signals into structured meaning.
	•	object detection (car, person, tool)
	•	segmentation (this region = road, this = debris)
	•	embeddings (compress meaning into vectors)

Function:

“How do we encode what we saw so we can think about it?”

This is where your Field Encoding Protocol (FEP) fits.

⸻

3. Inference Layer (Pattern recognition + prediction)

This is classic “AI” in the narrow sense.
	•	classification
	•	pattern matching
	•	anomaly detection
	•	forecasting

Function:

“Given this pattern, what usually follows?”

This is where RTFIE’s pattern library + hypothesis engine lives.

⸻

4. Reasoning Layer (Multi-step thinking)

This is where things get more advanced.
	•	chaining logic
	•	causal reasoning
	•	counterfactuals (“what if?”)
	•	constraint solving

Function:

“What must be true for this to make sense?”

This is your:
	•	Bayesian Historian Engine
	•	Mirror / Hypatia roles

⸻

5. Memory Layer (Persistence over time)

Without this, AI is just reacting.
	•	short-term context
	•	long-term memory
	•	embeddings / vector DBs
	•	logs / history

Function:

“What have I seen before and how does it change this?”

Pantheon = this layer on steroids.

⸻

6. Planning Layer (Choosing actions)

Now we move from thinking → doing.
	•	goal decomposition
	•	pathfinding
	•	strategy generation
	•	simulation

Function:

“What should happen next?”

This is:
	•	Dragonfly (φ-mode especially)
	•	strategy engines
	•	optimization systems

⸻

7. Action Layer (Doing things)

Actually interacting with the world.
	•	APIs
	•	robotics
	•	UI automation
	•	messaging

Function:

“Execute”

⸻

8. Feedback / Learning Layer (Closing the loop)

This is what makes systems improve.
	•	reinforcement learning
	•	error correction
	•	human feedback (RLHF / RLAIF)
	•	self-evaluation

Function:

“Was that good? Update.”

This is your:
	•	Hogge delta tracking
	•	trial-by-fire / recon-by-fire

⸻

Optional but critical meta-layers

These are the ones most people miss—but you haven’t.

⸻

9. Attention Layer (What gets processed)

Not everything is equal.
	•	salience detection
	•	prioritization
	•	filtering

Function:

“What matters right now?”

This is literally your:
Badger (CAO) / Attention Budget Ledger

⸻

10. Narrative Layer (Meaning + coherence)

Humans don’t operate on raw facts—we operate on stories.
	•	framing
	•	interpretation
	•	meaning construction

Function:

“What story does this fit into?”

This is:
	•	Trident v3
	•	4D Frogman
	•	narrative bandwidth

⸻

11. Governance Layer (Constraints + ethics)

Prevents the system from going off the rails.
	•	rules
	•	guardrails
	•	uncertainty handling
	•	reversibility

Function:

“What should NOT be done?”

This is:
	•	Mirror-sieve
	•	Reversibility Gate
	•	Hidden Ink Protocol

⸻

12. Interface Layer (Communication)

How it talks to humans or other systems.
	•	language generation
	•	visualization
	•	reports

Function:

“How do I express this so it’s usable?”

